  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "2 most important forms are cystic and alveolar caused by E. granulosus and E. multilocularis\nHumans are accidental immediate hosts by ingesting parasitic eggs from contaminated food, soil, water, or direct contact with definitive hosts\nUsual intermediate hosts-sheep, goat, swine, cattle, rodents and camel\nDefinitive hosts-dogs, cats, fox, and wolves\nIngested eggs then hatch, penetrate intestinal mucosa, and spread hematogenously to final destination to form cysts",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Asymptomatic for many years\nAbdominal cysts-\npain\n, distension,\nnausea/vomiting\nAlveolar abscess-\nchest pain\n,\nshortness of breath\n, chronic\ncough\nMusculoskeletal pain,\nblindness\n,\nheadache\n, and\nstroke\n-like symptoms if involving muscles, bones, eyes or brain",
